alist|[[Shinichi Yumoto]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 60&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 60 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Toghrul Asgarov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Besik Kudukhov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}} {{ref label|a|a|Men's freestyle 60 kg}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Coleman Scott]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Yogeshwar Dutt]]|IND|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 66&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 66 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tatsuhiro Yonemitsu]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sushil Kumar (wrestler)|Sushil Kumar]]|IND|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Akzhurek Tanatarov]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Liv\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]]|CUB|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 74&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 74 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jordan Burroughs]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sadegh Goudarzi]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Gabor Hatos]]|HUN|2012 Summer}} {{ref label|b|b|Men's freestyle 74 kg}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Denis Tsargush]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 84&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 84 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sharif Sharifov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jaime Espinal]]|PUR|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Dato Marsagishvili]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ehsan Lashgari]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 96&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 96 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jake Varner]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Valerii Andriitsev]]|UKR|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Giorgi Gogshelidze]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Khetag Gazyumov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 120&nbsp;kg{{ref label|c|c|Men's freestyle 120 kg}}<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 120 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Komeil Ghasemi]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Bilyal Makhov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tervel Dlagnev]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Daulet Shabanbay]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|}\n\n*{{note label|a|a|Men's freestyle 60 kg}} [[Besik Kudukhov]] of Russia won the silver medal, and while a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances in 2016, the IOC closed the proceedings after learning that Kudukhov died in a car accident in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=IOC Sanctions Wrestlers for Anti-Doping Violations at Beijing 2008 and London 2012 |url=https://unitedworldwrestling.org/article/todo%20 |publisher=[[United World Wrestling|FILA]] |accessdate=22 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228124421/https://unitedworldwrestling.org/article/todo%20 |archive-date=28 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*{{note label|b|b|Men's freestyle 74 kg}} [[Soslan Tigiev]] of Uzbekistan originally won the bronze medal, but he was disqualified in 2016 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-strips-uzbek-wrestler-of-london-bronze|title=IOC strips Uzbek wrestler of London bronze - Olympic News|date=2016-07-21|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitedworldwrestling.org/database|title=Database {{!}} United World Wrestling|website=unitedworldwrestling.org|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n*{{note label|c|c|Men's freestyle 120 kg}} [[Davit Modzmanashvili]] of Georgia originally won the silver medal, but was disqualified in January 2019 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-sanctions-one-athlete-for-failing-anti-doping-tests-at-london-2012|title=IOC sanctions one athlete for failing anti-doping tests at London 2012|date=2019-01-17|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> [[Artur Taymazov]] of Uzbekistan originally won the gold medal, but was disqualified in July 2019 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-sanctions-one-athlete-for-failing-anti-doping-tests-at-london-2012-3|title=IOC sanctions one athlete for failing anti-doping tests at London 2012|date=2019-07-23|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\n===Women's freestyle===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 48&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 48 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Hitomi Obara]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}  \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Mariya Stadnik]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}  \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Clarissa Chun]]|USA|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Carol Huynh]]|CAN|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 55&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 55 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Saori Yoshida]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tonya Verbeek]]|CAN|2012 Summer}}   \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jackeline Renter\u00eda]]|COL|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Yuliya Ratkevich]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 63&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 63 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Kaori Icho]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jing Ruixue]]|CHN|2012 Summer}}  \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Lubov Volosova]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Soronzonboldyn Battsetseg]]|MGL|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 72&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 72 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Natalia Vorobieva]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Stanka Zlateva]]|BUL|2012 Summer}}   \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Guzel Manyurova]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Maider Unda]]|ESP|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/ |title=Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics (London2012.com) |access-date=23 July 2018 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130228084337/http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/ |archive-date=28 February 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{SR/Olympics sport at games}}\n* [http://www.fila-wrestling.com/ International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles]\n\n{{Events at the 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Wrestling at the Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{coord|51.5075|N|0.0297|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2012 Summer Olympics events]]\n[[Category:Wrestling at the Summer Olympics|2012]]\n[[Category:Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:2012 in sport wrestling]]\n[[Category:International wrestling competitions hosted by the United Kingdom|Wrestling]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n| event       = Wrestling\n| games       = 2012 Summer\n| image       = Wrestling, London 2012.png\n| image_size  = 150px\n| venue       = [[ExCeL London]]\n| dates       = 5\u201312 August 2012\n| competitors = 344\n| nations     = 71\n| prev        = [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008]]\n| next        = [[Wrestling at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016]]\n}}\n{{WrestlingAt2012SummerOlympics}}\n[[File:ExCel Exhibition Centre.jpg|thumb|right|200px|ExCel Exhibition Centre]]\n\n'''Wrestling at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]]''' were held between 5 and 12 August, the final day of the Games, at [[ExCeL London]]. It was split into two disciplines, [[Freestyle wrestling|Freestyle]] and [[Greco-Roman wrestling|Greco-Roman]] which were further divided into different weight categories. Men competed in both disciplines whereas women only took part in the freestyle events, with 18 [[gold medal]]s awarded. [[Amateur wrestling|Wrestling]] has been contested at every modern [[Summer Olympic Games]], except [[1900 Summer Olympics|Paris 1900]].\n\n==Competition format==\n19 men or 18 women competed in each division, plus 6 others allocated either to the host country or by the tripartite commission into divisions yet to be determined prior to the Olympics. Wrestlers determined by lot competed in qualification rounds to reduce the number to 16, thereafter proceeding by simple knockout to determine the finalists who competed for gold and silver. The two groups of wrestlers respectively defeated in the 3 or 4 bouts of the two finalists competed in two serial elimination repechages, with the victor in each repechage being awarded bronze.\n\n==Competition schedule==\n<small>All times are [[British Summer Time]] ([[UTC+01:00|UTC+1]])</small>\n\n===Men's Greco-Roman===\n{|class=wikitable\n! Date !! Time !! Event\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Sunday 5 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 55&nbsp;kg & 74&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''55&nbsp;kg & 74&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Monday 6 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 60&nbsp;kg, 84&nbsp;kg & 120&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''60&nbsp;kg, 84&nbsp;kg & 120&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Tuesday 7 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 66&nbsp;kg & 96&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''66&nbsp;kg & 96&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|}\n\n===Women's freestyle===\n{|class=wikitable\n! Date !! Time !! Event\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Wednesday 8 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 48&nbsp;kg & 63&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''48&nbsp;kg & 63 repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Thursday 9 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 55&nbsp;kg & 72&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''55&nbsp;kg & 72&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|}\n\n===Men's freestyle===\n{|class=wikitable\n! Date !! Time !! Event\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Friday 10 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 55&nbsp;kg & 74&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''55&nbsp;kg & 74&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Saturday 11 August ||13:00\u201315:45 || 60&nbsp;kg, 84&nbsp;kg & 120&nbsp;kg qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''17:45\u201320:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''60&nbsp;kg, 84&nbsp;kg & 120&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Sunday 12 August ||08:30\u201311:15 || 66&nbsp;kg & 96&nbsp;kg Qualifications; 1/8 finals; quarterfinals; semifinals\n|-\n|style=background:lemonchiffon|'''12:45\u201315:15''' || style=background:lemonchiffon|'''66&nbsp;kg & 96&nbsp;kg repechage rounds, bronze & gold'''\n|}\n\nSource:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tickets.london2012.com/browse |title=Search events |publisher=London 2012 Olympic Games and Paralympic Games |accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Qualification==\n{{details|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification}}\n\n==Participating nations==\n344 wrestlers from 71 nations participated at the 2012 Olympics\n\n{{col-begin}}{{col-4}}\n*{{flagIOC|ALG|2012 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|ASA|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|ARG|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|ARM|2012 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|AUS|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|AUT|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|AZE|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|BLR|2012 Summer|11}}\n*{{flagIOC|BRA|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|BUL|2012 Summer|9}}\n*{{flagIOC|CMR|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|CAN|2012 Summer|9}}\n*{{flagIOC|CAF|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|CHI|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|CHN|2012 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|COL|2012 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|CIV|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|CRO|2012 Summer|2}}\n{{col-4}}\n*{{flagIOC|CUB|2012 Summer|12}}\n*{{flagIOC|CZE|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|DEN|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|ECU|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|EGY|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|EST|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|FIN|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|FRA|2012 Summer|6}}\n*{{flagIOC|GEO|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|GER|2012 Summer|4}}\n*{{flagIOC|GBR|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|GRE|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|GUM|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|GBS|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|HON|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|HUN|2012 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|IND|2012 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|IRI|2012 Summer|13}}\n{{col-4}}\n*{{flagIOC|IRQ|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|ITA|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|JPN|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|KAZ|2012 Summer|15}}\n*{{flagIOC|KGZ|2012 Summer|4}}\n*{{flagIOC|LAT|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|LTU|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|MAD|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|MEX|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|FSM|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|MDA|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|MGL|2012 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|MAR|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|NAM|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|NGR|2012 Summer|4}}\n*{{flagIOC|PRK|2012 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|NOR|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|POL|2012 Summer|4}}\n{{col-4}}\n*{{flagIOC|PUR|2012 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|ROU|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|RUS|2012 Summer|16}}\n*{{flagIOC|SEN|2012 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|SRB|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|KOR|2012 Summer|9}}\n*{{flagIOC|ESP|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|SWE|2012 Summer|6}}\n*{{flagIOC|SUI|2012 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|TJK|2012 Summer|4}}\n*{{flagIOC|TUN|2012 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|TUR|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|UKR|2012 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|USA|2012 Summer|17}}\n*{{flagIOC|UZB|2012 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|VEN|2012 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|VIE|2012 Summer|1}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Medal table==\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagIOC\n | event          = 2012 Summer\n | team           = \n | gold_RUS = 4 | silver_RUS = 3 | bronze_RUS = 4\n | gold_IRI = 4 | silver_IRI = 1 | bronze_IRI = 1\n | gold_JPN = 4 | silver_JPN = 0 | bronze_JPN = 2\n | gold_AZE = 2 | silver_AZE = 2 | bronze_AZE = 3\n | gold_USA = 2 | silver_USA = 0 | bronze_USA = 3\n | gold_CUB = 1 | silver_CUB = 0 | bronze_CUB = 1\n | gold_KOR = 1 | silver_KOR = 0 | bronze_KOR = 0\n | gold_GEO = 0 | silver_GEO = 2 | bronze_GEO = 3\n | gold_HUN = 0 | silver_HUN = 1 | bronze_HUN = 2\n | gold_ARM = 0 | silver_ARM = 1 | bronze_ARM = 1\n | gold_CAN = 0 | silver_CAN = 1 | bronze_CAN = 1\n | gold_IND = 0 | silver_IND = 1 | bronze_IND = 1\n | gold_BUL = 0 | silver_BUL = 1 | bronze_BUL = 0\n | gold_CHN = 0 | silver_CHN = 1 | bronze_CHN = 0\n | gold_EGY = 0 | silver_EGY = 1 | bronze_EGY = 0\n | gold_EST = 0 | silver_EST = 1 | bronze_EST = 0\n | gold_PUR = 0 | silver_PUR = 1 | bronze_PUR = 0\n | gold_UKR = 0 | silver_UKR = 1 | bronze_UKR = 0\n | gold_KAZ = 0 | silver_KAZ = 0 | bronze_KAZ = 4\n | gold_SWE = 0 | silver_SWE = 0 | bronze_SWE = 2\n | gold_COL = 0 | silver_COL = 0 | bronze_COL = 1\n | gold_FRA = 0 | silver_FRA = 0 | bronze_FRA = 1\n | gold_LTU = 0 | silver_LTU = 0 | bronze_LTU = 1\n | gold_MGL = 0 | silver_MGL = 0 | bronze_MGL = 1\n | gold_PRK = 0 | silver_PRK = 0 | bronze_PRK = 1\n | gold_POL = 0 | silver_POL = 0 | bronze_POL = 1\n | gold_ESP = 0 | silver_ESP = 0 | bronze_ESP = 1\n | gold_TUR = 0 | silver_TUR = 0 | bronze_TUR = 1\n}}\n\n==Medal summary==\n\n===Men's Greco-Roman===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 55&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 55 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Hamid Sourian]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Rovshan Bayramov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[P\u00e9ter M\u00f3dos]]|HUN|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Mingiyan Semenov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 60&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 60 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Omid Norouzi]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Revaz Lashkhi]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Zaur Kuramagomedov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ryutaro Matsumoto]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 66&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 66 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Kim Hyeon-woo]]|KOR|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tam\u00e1s L\u0151rincz]]|HUN|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Manuchar Tskhadaia]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Steeve Gu\u00e9not]]|FRA|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 74&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 74 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Roman Vlasov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Arsen Julfalakyan]]|ARM|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Aleksandr Kazakevi\u010d]]|LTU|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Emin Ahmadov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 84&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 84 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Alan Khugayev]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Karam Gaber]]|EGY|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Daniyal Gadzhiyev]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Damian Janikowski]]|POL|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 96&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 96 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ghasem Rezaei]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Rustam Totrov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Artur Aleksanyan]]|ARM|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jimmy Lidberg]]|SWE|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 120&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 120 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Mija\u00edn L\u00f3pez]]|CUB|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Heiki Nabi]]|EST|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[R\u0131za Kayaalp]]|TUR|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Johan Eur\u00e9n]]|SWE|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Men's freestyle===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 55&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 55 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Dzhamal Otarsultanov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Vladimer Khinchegashvili]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Yang Kyong-il]]|PRK|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Shinichi Yumoto]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 60&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 60 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Toghrul Asgarov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Besik Kudukhov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}} {{ref label|a|a|Men's freestyle 60 kg}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Coleman Scott]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Yogeshwar Dutt]]|IND|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 66&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 66 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tatsuhiro Yonemitsu]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sushil Kumar (wrestler)|Sushil Kumar]]|IND|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Akzhurek Tanatarov]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Liv\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]]|CUB|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 74&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 74 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jordan Burroughs]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2|  {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sadegh Goudarzi]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Gabor Hatos]]|HUN|2012 Summer}} {{ref label|b|b|Men's freestyle 74 kg}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Denis Tsargush]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 84&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 84 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sharif Sharifov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jaime Espinal]]|PUR|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Dato Marsagishvili]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ehsan Lashgari]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 96&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 96 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jake Varner]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Valerii Andriitsev]]|UKR|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Giorgi Gogshelidze]]|GEO|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Khetag Gazyumov]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 120&nbsp;kg{{ref label|c|c|Men's freestyle 120 kg}}<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 120 kg}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Komeil Ghasemi]]|IRI|2012 Summer}}\n|rowspan=2| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Bilyal Makhov]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tervel Dlagnev]]|USA|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n| {{flagIOCmedalist|[[Daulet Shabanbay]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|}\n\n*{{note label|a|a|Men's freestyle 60 kg}} [[Besik Kudukhov]] of Russia won the silver medal, and while a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances in 2016, the IOC closed the proceedings after learning that Kudukhov died in a car accident in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=IOC Sanctions Wrestlers for Anti-Doping Violations at Beijing 2008 and London 2012 |url=https://unitedworldwrestling.org/article/todo%20 |publisher=[[United World Wrestling|FILA]] |accessdate=22 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228124421/https://unitedworldwrestling.org/article/todo%20 |archive-date=28 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*{{note label|b|b|Men's freestyle 74 kg}} [[Soslan Tigiev]] of Uzbekistan originally won the bronze medal, but he was disqualified in 2016 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-strips-uzbek-wrestler-of-london-bronze|title=IOC strips Uzbek wrestler of London bronze - Olympic News|date=2016-07-21|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitedworldwrestling.org/database|title=Database {{!}} United World Wrestling|website=unitedworldwrestling.org|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n*{{note label|c|c|Men's freestyle 120 kg}} [[Davit Modzmanashvili]] of Georgia originally won the silver medal, but was disqualified in January 2019 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-sanctions-one-athlete-for-failing-anti-doping-tests-at-london-2012|title=IOC sanctions one athlete for failing anti-doping tests at London 2012|date=2019-01-17|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> [[Artur Taymazov]] of Uzbekistan originally won the gold medal, but was disqualified in July 2019 after a retest of his 2012 sample tested positive for banned substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-sanctions-one-athlete-for-failing-anti-doping-tests-at-london-2012-3|title=IOC sanctions one athlete for failing anti-doping tests at London 2012|date=2019-07-23|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\n===Women's freestyle===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 48&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 48 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Hitomi Obara]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}  \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Mariya Stadnik]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}  \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Clarissa Chun]]|USA|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Carol Huynh]]|CAN|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 55&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 55 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Saori Yoshida]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Tonya Verbeek]]|CAN|2012 Summer}}   \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jackeline Renter\u00eda]]|COL|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Yuliya Ratkevich]]|AZE|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 63&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 63 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Kaori Icho]]|JPN|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jing Ruixue]]|CHN|2012 Summer}}  \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Lubov Volosova]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Soronzonboldyn Battsetseg]]|MGL|2012 Summer}}  \n|-\n|rowspan=2| 72&nbsp;kg<br/>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 72 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Natalia Vorobieva]]|RUS|2012 Summer}}   \n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Stanka Zlateva]]|BUL|2012 Summer}}   \n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Guzel Manyurova]]|KAZ|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Maider Unda]]|ESP|2012 Summer}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/ |title=Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics (London2012.com) |access-date=23 July 2018 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130228084337/http://www.london2012.com/wrestling/ |archive-date=28 February 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{SR/Olympics sport at games}}\n* [http://www.fila-wrestling.com/ International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles]\n\n{{Events at the 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Wrestling at the Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{coord|51.5075|N|0.0297|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2012 Summer Olympics events]]\n[[Category:Wrestling at the Summer Olympics|2012]]\n[[Category:Wrestling at the 2012 Summer Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:2012 in sport wrestling]]\n[[Category:International wrestling competitions hosted by the United Kingdom|Wrestling]]\n", "name_user": "Mohsen1248", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrestling_at_the_2012_Summer_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Scharfrichterhaus", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Primary sources|date=July 2006}}\n\n[[File:Scharfrichterhaus-01.jpg|thumb|250px|The Scharfrichterhaus]]\nThe '''Scharfrichterhaus''' (executioner\u2019s house) in [[Passau]], [[Germany]], is designated as a national historical treasure and was built circa 1200. Located on \"Milk Street\", it was the official residence for the [[Scharfrichter]] ([[executioner]]) of the city of Passau. It is now a jazz and cabaret stage on which political cabaret is performed.\n\n== History ==\nEarly historical documents, from the 13th century until 1443, mention the building as the feared \"Prislig\" prison. Around 1620, during the 30 years war, then-executioner Kaspar would distribute small slips of paper that would make the owner invulnerable. This went into the history books as \"Passauerkunst\" or Art of Passau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allgerman.com/passau.htm|title=Passau|archive-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn the 1970s, the city of Passau was under the very strong influence of the conservatives of the [[Christian Social Union of Bavaria]], the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Passau]], and the Passauer press ([[Passauer Neue Presse]], PNP). Consequently, a counter cultural movement developed and a political cabaret was formed in Passau. The main cabaret performers in this movement were [[Bruno Jonas]] and [[Siegfried Zimmerschied]].{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn opposition to this counter culture movement, the chief editor of the PNP established a news embargo on the cabaret organization. The \"Generalvikar\" (high Catholic Church functionary) of the diocese took the movement to the court charging blasphemy. As a result, the city of Passau imposed a ban on the cabaret\u2019s performances.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe Scharfrichterhaus of today was founded in March 1977 by [[Walter Landshuter]] and [[Edgar Liegl]]. It has developed quickly to be an important jazz and cabaret stage on which political cabaret is performed. In 1979, the [[Passauer Cabaret Days]] was celebrated for the first time. This is a festival for art, theatre, music and cabaret. Since 1983 the Scharfrichterhaus, in collaboration with the Bavarian TV channel and a Munich newspaper, awarded the \"[[Executioner\u2019s Hatchet]]\". German comedian [[Hape Kerkeling]] received this award in 1983.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe Scharfrichterhaus, a place of cultural communication, as it names itself, is even known beyond the regional and national borders.{{Cn|date=August 2015}} Musicians and cabaret artists offer entertainment in a special atmosphere. Events in the Scharfrichterhaus include regular performances of jazz, readings, cabaret, chanson or theatre. Due to space restrictions, some of the events take place in the nearby \"Redoute Passau\".\n\n== Modern features ==\nToday the Scharfrichterhaus has two main features for visitors. The first is a cafe that is part of the house and is modeled after a Viennese coffeehouse of the 19th and 20th century. The second feature is a restaurant with selected food and wine, and an additional wine-cellar.\n\n[[File:Passau Scharfrichterhaus Innenhof.jpg|thumb|left|The patio of the Scharfrichterhaus]]\nThe Scharfrichterhaus also contains the independent \"Scharfrichter-Cinema\". The Passauer film operator [[Manfred Vesper]] has rented its rooms since 5 February 1987, based on an initiative from Walter Landshuter for a cinema, fitting to the remaining program of the Scharfrichterhaus. Those rooms had been already used for some years to present a weekly ambitious cinema, but these events had not been widely accepted by the audience.\n\nA distinct feature of the new institution is the repertory cinema. With its detailed program the visitor knows already weeks in advance what is available. A program guide called \"Trailer\", the cinema's main advertising, is spread out in a circulation of 6000 copies and laid out in various shops, sent by post or email. The selection of movies, which fit into the other Scharfrichterhaus program, aims to reach viewers interested in non-mainstream movies and is primarily chosen by Vesper.\n\nIn addition, there is also a program advisory board. It consists of Landshuter and Vesper, two professors of the university of Passau, and two employees who work out together the different film rows at their regular meetings and submit them to the annual competition of the Federal Minister of the Interior for support of the cinema (German: ''Filmf\u00f6rderanstalt''). Up to now every year the cinema won the prize of 5000 euro.{{Cn|date=August 2015}} These prizes must be used for re-investments.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Scharfrichterhaus in Passau}}\n* [http://www.scharfrichter-haus.de/ Official Website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{coord|48|34|30|N|13|28|10|E|display=title|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Passau]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Primary sources|date=July 2006}}\n\n[[File:Scharfrichterhaus-01.jpg|thumb|250px|The Scharfrichterhaus]]\nThe '''Scharfrichterhaus''' (executioner\u2019s house) in [[Passau]], [[Germany]], is designated as a national historical treasure and was built circa 1200. Located on \"Milk Street\", it was the official residence for the [[Scharfrichter]] ([[executioner]]) of the city of Passau. It is now a jazz and cabaret stage on which political cabaret is performed.\n\n== History ==\nEarly historical documents, from the 13th century until 1443, mention the building as the feared \"Prislig\" prison. Around 1620, during the 30 years war, then-executioner Kaspar would distribute small slips of paper that would make the owner invulnerable. This went into the history books as \"Passauerkunst\" or Art of Passau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allgerman.com/passau.htm|title=Passau|archive-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn the 1970s, the city of Passau was under the very strong influence of the conservatives of the [[Christian Social Union of Bavaria]], the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Passau]], and the Passauer press ([[Passauer Neue Presse]], PNP). Consequently, a counter cultural movement developed and a political cabaret was formed in Passau. The main cabaret performers in this movement were [[Bruno Jonas]] and [[Siegfried Zimmerschied]].{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nIn opposition to this counter culture movement, the chief editor of the PNP established a news embargo on the cabaret organization. The \"Generalvikar\" (high Catholic Church functionary) of the diocese took the movement to the court charging blasphemy. As a result, the city of Passau imposed a ban on the cabaret\u2019s performances.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe Scharfrichterhaus of today was founded in March 1977 by [[Walter Landshuter]] and [[Edgar Liegl]]. It has developed quickly to be an important jazz and cabaret stage on which political cabaret is performed. In 1979, the [[Passauer Cabaret Days]] was celebrated for the first time. This is a festival for art, theatre, music and cabaret. Since 1983 the Scharfrichterhaus, in collaboration with the Bavarian TV channel and a Munich newspaper, awarded the \"[[Executioner\u2019s Hatchet]]\". German comedian [[Hape Kerkeling]] received this award in 1983.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe Scharfrichterhaus, a place of cultural communication, as it names itself, is even known beyond the regional and national borders.{{Cn|date=August 2015}} Musicians and cabaret artists offer entertainment in a special atmosphere. Events in the Scharfrichterhaus include regular performances of jazz, readings, cabaret, chanson or theatre. Due to space restrictions, some of the events take place in the nearby \"Redoute Passau\".\n\n== Modern features ==\nToday the Scharfrichterhaus has two main features for visitors. The first is a cafe that is part of the house and is modeled after a Viennese coffeehouse of the 19th and 20th century. The second feature is a restaurant with selected food and wine, and an additional wine-cellar.\n\n[[File:Passau Scharfrichterhaus Innenhof.jpg|thumb|left|The patio of the Scharfrichterhaus]]\nThe Scharfrichterhaus also contains the independent \"Scharfrichter-Cinema\". The Passauer film operator [[Manfred Vesper]] has rented its rooms since 5 February 1987, based on an initiative from Walter Landshuter for a cinema, fitting to the remaining program of the Scharfrichterhaus. Those rooms had been already used for some years to present a weekly ambitious cinema, but these events had not been widely accepted by the audience.\n\nA distinct feature of the new institution is the repertory cinema. With its detailed program the visitor knows already weeks in advance what is available. A program guide called \"Trailer\", the cinema's main advertising, is spread out in a circulation of 6000 copies and laid out in various shops, sent by post or email. The selection of movies, which fit into the other Scharfrichterhaus program, aims to reach viewers interested in non-mainstream movies and is primarily chosen by Vesper.\n\nIn addition, there is also a program advisory board. It consists of Landshuter and Vesper, two professors of the university of Passau, and two employees who work out together the different film rows at their regular meetings and submit them to the annual competition of the Federal Minister of the Interior for support of the cinema (German: ''Filmf\u00f6rderanstalt''). Up to now every year the cinema won the price of 5000 euro.{{Cn|date=August 2015}} These prices must be used for re-investments.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Scharfrichterhaus in Passau}}\n* [http://www.scharfrichter-haus.de/ Official Website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{coord|48|34|30|N|13|28|10|E|display=title|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Passau]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern features:Typo fixing, replaced: price \u2192 prize (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scharfrichterhaus"}
{"title_page": "Gianpiero Marini", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Gianpiero Marini\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1951|2|25|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]], Italy\n| height = 1.76 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]]\n| years1 = 1968\u20131969\n| years2 = 1969\u20131970\n| years3 = 1970\u20131972\n| years4 = 1971\u20131972\n| years5 = 1972\u20131975\n| years6 = 1975\u20131986\n| clubs1 = [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]]\n| clubs2 = [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]]\n| clubs3 = [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]]\n| clubs4 = [[Unione Triestina 2012 S.S.D.|Triestina]]\n| clubs5 = [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]]\n| clubs6 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| caps1 = 19\n| goals1 = 0\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| caps3 = 15\n| goals3 = 0\n| caps4 = 25\n| goals4 = 4\n| caps5 = 89\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = 375\n| goals6 = 13\n| totalcaps = 523\n| totalgoals = 17\n| nationalyears1 = 1980\u20131983\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 20\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 1994\n| managerclubs1 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| manageryears2 = 1997\n| managerclubs2 = [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n| manageryears3 = 1997\u20131999\n| managerclubs3 = [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]]\n| manageryears4 = 1999\u20132000\n| managerclubs4 = [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n| manageryears5 = 2001\n| managerclubs5 = Italy B\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalTeam|{{fb|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1982 FIFA World Cup|Spain 1982]]|}}\n}}\n'''Gianpiero Marini''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292am\u02c8pj\u025b\u02d0ro ma\u02c8ri\u02d0ni}}; born 25 February 1951) is an Italian former professional [[Association football manager|football manager]] and [[Association football|player]], who played as a [[midfielder]]. A strong and hard-working [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], Marini played for several Italian clubs throughout his career, in particular [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], where he won a [[Serie A]] title and two [[Coppa Italia]] titles during his 11 seasons with the club. At international level, he represented Italy on 20 occasions between 1980 and 1983, and was a member of the team that won the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nAs a manager, Marini also coached [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] in 1994, as well as [[Calcio Como|Como]], [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]], and the Italy B side.\n\n==Club career==\nMarini was born in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]]. Nicknamed ''Malik'' by fans, he played 256 matches in [[Serie A]], scoring 10 goals. Throughout his career, he played for several teams, including [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]], [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]], [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]], [[U.S. Triestina Calcio|Triestina]] and most notably [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale Milano]]. With Inter, he won a [[Serie A]] title (\"Scudetto\") during the [[1979\u201380 Serie A|1979\u201380]] season, and two [[Coppa Italia]] titles in 1978 and 1982.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pianeta-calcio.it/?page=vedi_incontri_vip&id=247|title=IO, \"PIEDONE\" MARINI|website=pianeta-calcio.it|language=Italian|accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nWith [[Italy national football team|Italy]], Marini obtained 20 caps between 1980 and 1983, and he represented Italy in their victorious [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] campaign, which enabled him to become a World Champion.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=174734/index.html Gianpiero Marini Statistics] [[FIFA]]. Retrieved 2 February 2010.</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nMarini was known in particular for his strength, work-rate, and ability to break down plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], as well as his powerful and accurate striking ability from distance.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.it/sport/calcio/bonimba-voce-inter/bagni-inter-5-mediani-scudetto-50-anni/|title=Bagni: \"I miei 5 mediani scudettati per 50 anni di Inter\"|publisher=Panorama.it|language=Italian|author1=Filippo Nassetti|date=31 March 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcinter1908.it/primo-piano/beccalossi-io-e-muller-non-ci-potevamo-vedere-ecco-perche-oriali-mi-diceva/?refresh_ce-cp|title=BECCALOSSI: \"IO E MULLER NON CI POTEVAMO VEDERE, ECCO PERCH\u00c9. ORIALI MI DICEVA\u2026\"|publisher=F.C. Inter 1908|language=Italian|date=5 March 2016|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nAs coach, Marini also managed [[Internazionale]] during the [[1993\u201394 Serie A|1993\u201394]], where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] in [[1994 UEFA Cup Final|1994]], despite narrowly avoiding relegation in the league; he later also coached [[Calcio Como|Como]] on two different occasions (1997; 1999\u20132000), as well as [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]] (1997\u201399), and the Italy B side in 2001.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n====Club====\n'''Inter'''<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1979\u201380 Serie A|1979\u201380]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1977\u201378 Coppa Italia|1977\u201378]], 1981\u201382\n\n====International====\n'''Italy'''<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]\n\n===Coach===\n'''Inter'''<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UEFA Cup / Europa League winning managers}}\n{{Italy Squad 1982 World Cup}}\n{{F.C. Internazionale Milano managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marini, Gianpiero}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lodi, Lombardy]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Reggina 1914 players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan managers]]\n[[Category:Serie A managers]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Varese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footy-midfielder-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2010}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Gianpiero Marini\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1951|2|25|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]], [[Italy]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.76}}\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1= \n| youthclubs1= [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]]\n| years1 = 1968\u20131969 | years2 = 1969\u20131970 | years3 = 1970\u20131972 | years4 = 1971\u20131972 | years5 = 1972\u20131975 | years6 =1975\u20131986\n| clubs1 = [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]] | clubs2 = [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]] | clubs3 = [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]] | clubs4 = [[Unione Triestina 2012 S.S.D.|Triestina]] | clubs5 = [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]] | clubs6 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| caps1 = 19 | goals1 = 0 | caps2 = 0 | goals2 = 0 | caps3 = 15 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 = 25 | goals4 = 4 | caps5 = 89 | goals5 = 0 | caps6 = 375 | goals6 = 13\n| nationalyears1= 1980\u20131983\n| nationalteam1= [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps1= 20 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1= 1994\n| managerclubs1= [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| manageryears2= 1997\n| managerclubs2= [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n| manageryears3= 1997\u20131999\n| managerclubs3= [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]]\n| manageryears4= 1999\u20132000\n| managerclubs4= [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n| manageryears5= 2001\n| managerclubs5= Italy B\n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalTeam|{{fb|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1982 FIFA World Cup|Spain 1982]]|}}\n}}\n'''Gianpiero Marini''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292am\u02c8pj\u025b\u02d0ro ma\u02c8ri\u02d0ni}}; born 25 February 1951 in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]]) is an [[Italians|Italian]] former [[Association football manager|football manager]] and [[Association football|player]], who played as a [[midfielder]]. A strong and hard-working [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], Marini played for several Italian clubs throughout his career, in particular [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], where he won a [[Serie A]] title and two [[Coppa Italia]] titles during his 11 seasons with the club. At international level, he represented Italy on 20 occasions between 1980 and 1983, and was a member of the team that won the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nAs a manager, Marini also coached [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] in 1994, as well as [[Calcio Como|Como]], [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]], and the Italy B side.\n\n==Club career==\nNicknamed ''Malik'' by fans, Marini played 256 matches in [[Serie A]], scoring 10 goals. Throughout his career, he played for several teams, including [[A.C. Fanfulla 1874|Fanfulla]], [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]], [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]], [[U.S. Triestina Calcio|Triestina]] and most notably [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale Milano]]. With Inter, he won a [[Serie A]] title (\"Scudetto\") during the [[1979\u201380 Serie A|1979\u201380]] season, and two [[Coppa Italia]] titles in 1978 and 1982.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pianeta-calcio.it/?page=vedi_incontri_vip&id=247|title=IO, \"PIEDONE\" MARINI|website=pianeta-calcio.it|language=Italian|accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nWith [[Italy national football team|Italy]], Marini obtained 20 caps between 1980 and 1983, and he represented Italy in their victorious [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] campaign, which enabled him to become a World Champion.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/><ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=174734/index.html Gianpiero Marini Statistics] [[FIFA]]. Retrieved 2 February 2010.</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nMarini was known in particular for his strength, work-rate, and ability to break down plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], as well as his powerful and accurate striking ability from distance.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.it/sport/calcio/bonimba-voce-inter/bagni-inter-5-mediani-scudetto-50-anni/|title=Bagni: \"I miei 5 mediani scudettati per 50 anni di Inter\"|publisher=Panorama.it|language=Italian|author1=Filippo Nassetti|date=31 March 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcinter1908.it/primo-piano/beccalossi-io-e-muller-non-ci-potevamo-vedere-ecco-perche-oriali-mi-diceva/?refresh_ce-cp|title=BECCALOSSI: \"IO E MULLER NON CI POTEVAMO VEDERE, ECCO PERCH\u00c9. ORIALI MI DICEVA\u2026\"|publisher=F.C. Inter 1908|language=Italian|date=5 March 2016|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nAs coach, Marini also managed [[Internazionale]] during the [[1993\u201394 Serie A|1993\u201394]], where he won the [[UEFA Cup]] in [[1994 UEFA Cup Final|1994]], despite narrowly avoiding relegation in the league; he later also coached [[Calcio Como|Como]] on two different occasions (1997; 1999\u20132000), as well as [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]] (1997\u201399), and the Italy B side in 2001.<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n====Club====\n;[[Internazionale Milano FC|Inter]]<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1979\u201380 Serie A|1979\u201380]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1977\u201378 Coppa Italia|1977\u201378]], 1981\u201382\n\n====International====\n;[[Italy national football team|Italy]]<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]\n\n===Coach===\n;[[Internazionale Milano FC|Inter]]<ref name=\"IO, PIEDONE MARINI\"/>\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UEFA Cup / Europa League winning managers}}\n{{Italy Squad 1982 World Cup}}\n{{F.C. Internazionale Milano managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marini, Gianpiero}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lodi, Lombardy]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning managers]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Reggina 1914 players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan managers]]\n[[Category:Serie A managers]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Varese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footy-midfielder-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add totalcaps and totalgoals. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gianpiero_Marini"}
{"title_page": "List of units and formations of the British Army 2020", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nThe [[British Army]] as a result of the [[Army 2020|Army 2020 Refine]] reforms are organised into two main commands, [[Commander Field Army|Field Army]] and [[Commander Home Command|Home Command]], each commanded by a [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|lieutenant general]].\n\n[[Permanent Joint Headquarters]] (PJHQ) plans and executes UK-led joint and multinational operations, including those involving British Army units, and operationally commands UK forces assigned to multinational operations led by other nation-states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/the-permanent-joint-headquarters|title=The Permanent Joint Headquarters|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> For example, during [[Operation Telic]], the Chief of Joint Operations at PJHQ directed Major General [[Robin Brims]], the UK Land Contingent Commander, through the UK National Contingent Commander, [[Air Marshal]] [[Brian Burridge]].<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20171123124640/http://www.iraqinquiry.org.uk/media/247900/the-report-of-the-iraq-inquiry_section-80.pdf The Report of the Iraqi Inquiry: The Invasion], pages 7 & 8, paragraphs 23, 25, 26.</ref>\n\nBritish Army forces may also be deployed to NATO operations, which then are delegated by [[North Atlantic Council]] or other NATO bodies to the [[Supreme Allied Commander Europe]] who delegates the operation to relevant headquarters. PJHQ may still be involved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmdfence/347/34717.htm#note463 |title=Fourteenth Report: Lessons of Kosovo III THE CONDUCT OF THE CAMPAIGN:Command, Coordination and Intelligence  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 October 2000 |website=publications.parliament.uk |publisher=Defence Select Committee |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|UK Army 2018.png|4400px|Structure of the British Army 2018-19|550px|right}}\n\n== Field Army ==\n{{see also|Commander Field Army}}\nThe units under Field Army are:<ref name=\"aff\">[http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf Regular Army basing matrix by formation and unit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814181412/http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf |date=2016-08-14 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf Army 2020 Update] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610215557/http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf |date=June 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n* '''Reaction forces''' comprising [[16 Air Assault Brigade]] and 3rd (UK) Division of two armoured infantry brigades, the 12th and 20th Armoured Infantry Brigades, and two Strike brigades: 1st Strike Brigade and an as-yet-unnamed strike brigade, along with combat support units.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/9911295/Famed-Desert-Rats-to-lose-their-tanks-under-Army-cuts.html|title=Famed Desert Rats to lose their tanks under Army cuts|work=Telegraph|date=2013-03-05|accessdate=2013-03-09|last1=Kirkup|first1=James}}</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them as \"Armoured Infantry Brigades\"]</ref><ref name=\"Dec162\"/> 3rd UK Division is operationally affiliated with the [[Allied Rapid Reaction Corps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arrc.nato.int/about-us/formations |title=Assigned Formations |date= 31 January 2018 |website=arrc.nato.int |publisher=Allied Rapid Reaction Corps |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Adaptive forces''' comprising a 1st (UK) Division brigades, three of which (the 4th, 7th, and 51st) will be deployable.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them in order]</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexA.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex A]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexC.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex C]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''6th (UK) Division''' comprising surveillance, intelligence, reconnaissance, communications, electronic warfare, psychological operations.\n* '''Joint Helicopter Command''' which commands most of the UK's battlefield lift and attack helicopters for the Royal Navy, British Army and Royal Air Force.\n\nField Army gained initial operating capability on 30 November 2015 and was formed as a result of the  2015 Army Command Review. The Commander Field Army commands all the formations of the British Army's forces for operational tasks, its collective training and tactical doctrine organisations and includes the vast majority of the Army\u2019s fighting equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |title=Flag raised to signal new HQ Field Army |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=26 August 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124164925/http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== 1st (United Kingdom) Division ===\n* '''[[1st (United Kingdom) Division]]''',<ref name=\"Army 2019\">{{cite web |title=Army restructures to confront evolving threats |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/army-restructures-to-confront-evolving-threats |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref> in [[York]] (Adaptable Force)\n\n==== 4th Infantry Brigade and Headquarters North East ====\n{{Location map+ | United Kingdom\n| width = 330\n| 