|language=en|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>\n** [[Artists Rifles|21 (Artists) Special Air Service Regiment]], in London (Army Reserve)\n** [[23 Special Air Service Regiment (Reserve)|23 Special Air Service Regiment]], in [[Birmingham]] (Army Reserve)\n** Land Intelligence Fusion Centre, [[Hermitage, Berkshire|Hermitage]]\n** Defence Cultural Specialist Unit, Hermitage\n** Weapons Material and Personnel Exploitation Capacity, Hermitage\n** Specialist Group Military Intelligence, Hermitage\n\n==== 1st (United Kingdom) Signal Brigade ====\n* '''[[1st Signal Brigade (United Kingdom)|1st (United Kingdom) Signal Brigade]]''', in [[Innsworth]]\n** 299 Signal Squadron (Special Communications), in [[Bletchley]] supports{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} the [[United Kingdom|UK]]'s [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n** 22nd Signal Regiment, in [[Stafford]] supports NATO's Allied Rapid Reaction Corps\n** 30th Signal Regiment, in Stafford supports the PJHQ's deployable Joint Force Headquarters, Very High Readiness Field Hospital, the Air Assault Task Force and Joint Helicopter Command (to move to [[Beacon Barracks]])<ref name=ZacchiFOI /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/6th-united-kingdom-division/1st-signal-brigade/ |title=1st Signal Brigade |date=6 September 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n** ARRC Support Battalion, in Innsworth supports [[NATO]]'s Allied Rapid Reaction Corps\n** ''ARRC Military Police Battalion, in [[Winchester]] (Army Reserve)''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apply.army.mod.uk/what-we-offer/army-reserve-centres/south-east/winchester-worthy-down|title=Bray House - Winchester - Worthy Down - British Army Jobs|website=apply.army.mod.uk|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=1nM_Rgx_0WiMOspeCiA61vqxu97Y|title=Army Reserve Units|website=Google My Maps|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==== 11th Signal Brigade and Headquarters West Midlands ====\n* '''[[11th Signal Brigade and Headquarters West Midlands]]''', in [[Donnington, Telford|Donnington]]\n** National Reserve Headquarters, Royal Corps of Signals\n** ''[[37 Signal Regiment|37th (Wales and Western) Signal Regiment]], in [[Redditch]] (Army Reserve \u2013 paired with 1st and 16th Signal Regiments, in 7 Signal Group)''\n** ''[[39 (Skinners) Signal Regiment|39th (The Skinners) Signal Regiment]], in [[Bristol]] (Army Reserve \u2013 paired with 21st Signal Regiment, in 7 Signal Group)''\n** ''[[71 (Yeomanry) Signal Regiment|71st (City of London) Yeomanry Signal Regiment]], in [[Bexleyheath]] (Army Reserve \u2013 paired with 3rd Signal Regiment, in 7 Signal Group)''\n** 7 Signal Group, in Stafford\n*** [[1 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|1st Signal Regiment]], in [[Tidworth]]<ref name=ZacchiFOI />\n*** [[2 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|2nd Signal Regiment]], in [[York]]\n*** [[3 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|3rd Signal Regiment]], in Bulford\n*** 16th Signal Regiment, in Stafford\n*** [[21 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|21st Signal Regiment]], in [[Colerne]]\n*** [[32 (Scottish) Signal Regiment|32nd Signal Regiment]], in [[Glasgow]] (Army Reserve \u2013 paired with 2nd Signal Regiment)\n*** [[10 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|10th Signal Regiment]], in [[Corsham]]\n*** [[15 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|15th Signal Regiment (Information Systems)]], in [[Perham Down]]<ref name=ZacchiFOI />\n*** ''[[32nd (Scottish) Signal Regiment]], [[Glasgow]] (Army Reserve)''\n\n==== 77th Brigade ====\n* '''[[77th Brigade (United Kingdom)|77th Brigade]]''', in [[Denison Barracks|Hermitage]]\n** Information Activities (IA) Group - planning support focusing on the behavioural analysis of actors, audiences and adversaries\n** Task Group - deliver Information Activity and Outreach\n** Outreach Group - Security Capacity Building\n** Support Group - Combat Camera Teams, main reservists\n** [[Engineer and Logistic Staff Corps]]\n\n=== 16 Air Assault Brigade ===\n* '''[[16 Air Assault Brigade]]''', in [[Colchester Garrison|Colchester]] (Reaction Force)\n** [[216 Parachute Signal Squadron|216 Air Assault Signal Squadron]] at Merville Barracks\n** 226 Signal Squadron at Cawdor Barracks (under 14 Signal Reg for Admin)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/umbraco/Surface/Download/Get/11310|title=Royal Signals Interactive Map|last=|first=|publisher=[[Royal Corps of Signals]]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n** [[Pathfinder Platoon|The Pathfinder Platoon]]\n** [[2 PARA|2nd Battalion The Parachute Regiment]] at Merville Barracks\n** [[3 PARA|3rd Battalion The Parachute Regiment]] at Merville Barracks\n** [[4 PARA|4th Battalion The Parachute Regiment]]\n** 1st Battalion The Royal Gurkha Rifles (Air Assault Infantry), at [[Sir John Moore Barracks]]\n** 53 (Louisburg) Surveillance and Target Acquisition Air Assault Battery Royal Artillery (under [[5th Regiment Royal Artillery|5 Regiment Royal Artillery]] for Admin)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/5RegtRA/posts/3074166342607478|title=5th Regiment Royal Artillery - The Yorkshire Gunners|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n** [[7th Regiment Royal Horse Artillery]] (Light Artillery) at Merville Barracks\n*** [[A Battery, Honourable Artillery Company|A (1st City of London) Battery The Honourable Artillery Company]] (Light Artillery), at Finsbury Barracks (Army Reserve - under [[Honourable Artillery Company]] for Admin)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/6th-united-kingdom-division/1st-intelligence-surveillance-and-reconnaissance-brigade/honourable-artillery-company/|title=Honourable Artillery Company|website=www.army.mod.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n** 12 (Minden) Light Air Defence Battery Royal Artillery (under [[12 Regiment RA]] for Admin)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/artillery/regiments/24670.aspx|title=12 Regiment - British Army Website|date=2018-01-03|access-date=2019-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103084529/http://www.army.mod.uk/artillery/regiments/24670.aspx|archive-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n** 21 (Gibraltar 1779-83) Unmanned Air Systems Air Assault Battery Royal Artillery (UAS) (under [[32 Regiment Royal Artillery]] for Admin)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://21bty.org.uk/21-air-assault-battery/|title=21 Air Assault Battery|website=21 Air Defence Battery|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n** [[23 Engineer Regiment (Air Assault)|23rd Parachute Engineer Regiment Corps of Royal Engineers]] at Rock Barracks\n** [[13 Air Assault Regiment RLC|13th Air Assault Support Regiment Royal Logistic Corps]] at Merville Barracks\n** 16th Medical Regiment Royal Army Medical Corps at Merville Barracks\n*** 144 Parachute Medical Squadron (Army Reserve)\n** 156 Provost Company Corps of Royal Military Police at Reed Hall Lines (under 3 Regiment RMP for ADMIN)\n\n=== Joint Helicopter Command ===\n* '''[[Joint Helicopter Command]]''', in [[AAC Middle Wallop|Middle Wallop]] (reports to Commander Field Army)\n** [[1 Regiment Army Air Corps]], in [[RNAS Yeovilton (HMS Heron)|Yeovilton]] with [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] helicopters\n** [[2 Regiment Army Air Corps]] (Ground Crew Training), Middle Wallop\n** [[3 Regiment Army Air Corps]], in [[Wattisham Airfield|Wattisham]] with [[AgustaWestland Apache|Apache AH.1]] attack helicopters\n** [[4 Regiment Army Air Corps]], in Wattisham with Apache AH.1 attack helicopters\n** [[5 Regiment Army Air Corps]], in [[RAF Aldergrove|Aldergrove]] with [[A\u00e9rospatiale Gazelle|Westland Gazelle]] helicopters\n** [[6 Regiment Army Air Corps]], in [[Bury St Edmunds]] (Army Reserve)\n** 7 Regiment Army Air Corps (Flight Crew Training), in Middle Wallop\n** Commando Helicopter Force, in Yeovilton\n** [[47th Regiment Royal Artillery]], in [[Horne Barracks|Larkhill]] with [[Thales Watchkeeper WK450|Watchkeeper WK450]] [[unmanned aerial vehicles]]\n** 7th Battalion REME, in Wattisham\n\n== Home Command ==\n{{see also|Commander Home Command}}\nHome Command consists of:\n* '''Regional Command''' - to ensure delivery of a secure home front and forces and families in Brunei and Nepal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/regional-command/ |title=Regional Command |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019 }}</ref> When not engaged with operational commitments  or when units may report to the Standing Joint Commander (UK) or mission-specific training (e.g. when conducting routine civilian engagement, ranges, or ceremonial duties, units and formations may report through a Regional Point of Command (RPOC) to HQ [[Regional Command (British Army)|Regional Command]] at Andover.<ref>British Army, Transforming the British Army: An Update: July 2013, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> Regional Command, as of 1 August 2019, has 38th (Irish) Brigade and 160th (Welsh) Brigade permanently under its command as RPOCs.\n* '''London District''' - commands all the Army forces within the London area and conducts ceremonial events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/headquarters-london-district/ |title=Headquarters London District |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}.</ref>\n* '''Recruiting and Initial Training Command''' - recruits and trains soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/media/4612/adr007595-asm_guide.pdf |title=Digital Army: Using Social Media in the British Army |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 September 2018 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019 }}</ref>\n* '''Army Personnel Centre''' - deals with personnel issues and liaises with outside agencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/personnel-and-welfare/army-personnel-centre/ |title=Army Personnel Centre |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Sandhurst Group''' - deals with applications of army officers and trains such cadets at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/our-schools-and-colleges/rma-sandhurst/ |title=RMAS Sandhurst |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 August 2019 |website=army.mod.uk |publisher=British Army |access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Home Command (British Army)|Commander Home Command]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/our-people/senior-leaders/commander-home-command/ | title=Commander Home Command}}</ref> is also the Standing Joint Commander (UK) for responsible for the planning and execution of civil contingency operations within the UK landmass and territorial waters.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.themilitarytimes.co.uk/uncategorised/aldershot-becomes-home-to-headquarter-standing-joint-commander-uk/ |title = Aldershot becomes home to Headquarter Standing Joint Commander (UK) \u2022 the Military Times|date = 2017-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who we are|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/home-command/|website=Home Command|publisher=British Army|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===[[London District|Headquarters London District]]===\n* '''[[London District (British Army)|Headquarters London District]]''' at [[Horse Guards (building)|Horse Guards]] in [[London]]\n** 238 Signal Squadron, [[Royal Corps of Signals]] (provides all communications for London District, administered by [[10 Signal Regiment (United Kingdom)|10 Signal Regiment]])\n** [[Household Cavalry Mounted Regiment]] at [[Hyde Park Barracks, London|Hyde Park Barracks]]\n** 1st Battalion, [[Welsh Guards]], [[Combermere Barracks]] in [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]]\n** 1st Battalion, [[Grenadier Guards]], Lille Barracks in [[Aldershot]]\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|Nijmegen Company]], [[Grenadier Guards]] at [[Wellington Barracks]]\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|No 7 Company]], [[Coldstream Guards]] at Wellington Barracks\n** [[Guards Incremental Companies|F Company]], [[Scots Guards]] at Wellington Barracks\n**[[King's Troop Royal Horse Artillery]] at [[Royal Artillery Barracks]] in [[Woolwich]] with [[Ordnance QF 13-pounder|13-pounder]] guns for ceremonial duties\n** 20 Transport Squadron, [[Royal Logistic Corps]] based at [[Regent's Park Barracks]], (provides all the transport needs for London District and the Royal Household)\n**[[Royal Military School of Music]], at [[Kneller Hall]]\n\n=== Headquarters Regional Command ===\n[[Regional Command (British Army)|Headquarters Regional Command]] at Aldershot is commanded by a [[Major-General]]. It is the Army's HQ for the UK, Nepal and Brunei, administering Army bases in the UK and providing civil engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/formations-divisions-brigades/regional-command/ |title=Regional Command |publisher=British Army|website=army.mod.uk|date= |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==== Regional Points of Command ====\n* [[Headquarters North West (United Kingdom)|Headquarters North West]], [[Fulwood Barracks]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/ArmyintheNorth/about/?ref=page_internal|title=Army in the North|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n* [[Headquarters South West (United Kingdom)|Headquarters South West]], [[Jellalabad Barracks]]<ref name=\"HQSouthWest\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by-line.--> |title=Wiltshire Police pledge to be a forces friendly employer |url=https://www.wiltshire.police.uk/article/4689/Wiltshire-Police-pledge-to-be-a-forces-friendly-employer |work=Wiltshire Police |location=Devizes |date=28 June 2019 |access-date=19 August 2019 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://swlep.co.uk/docs/default-source/board-meetings/2017/25-may-2018/army-presentation-to-board-meeting-25-may-2017.pdf?sfvrsn=3fc214c5_4 |title=Army Update: Commander HQ South West Colonel James Coote DSO OBE |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=25 May 2017 |website=swlep.co.uk |publisher=Swindon & Wiltshire LEP |access-date=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 1st Military Police Brigade ====\n* '''[[1st Military Police Brigade]]''' in [[Marlborough Lines]], [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]]<ref name=ZacchiFOI /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/adjutant-generals-corps/provost/|title=Provost Marshal (Army) & 1st Military Police Brigade|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=14 October 2019|website=army.mod.uk|publisher=British Army|access-date=14 October 2019|quote=1 MP Brigade provide 'Police Support to the Force' at an operational level, usually overseas, and includes operational detention, support to security and stability policing. This is again supported by the RMP and MPS. The Brigade sits under the tactical command of 3 (UK) Div.}}</ref> CGS retains full responsibility over military police investigations while day-to-day control of 1 and 3 RMP rest with General Officer Commanding (GOC) 3rd UK Division. Administrative control of other Royal Military Police Brigade units rest under GOC Regional Command.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/615420/response/1473620/attach/3/20191122%20FOI12276%20Davis%20Military%20Police%20Response%20Letter%20ArmySec.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |title=RMP units |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=22 November 2019 |website=WhatDoTheyKnow |access-date=22 November 2019 |quote=Military Police capability remains under the command of the Chief of the General Staff (CGS) and retains full responsibility for investigations. To better coordinate the close support policing, the responsibility for day-to-day activities (tactical command) of 1st and 3rd Regiments Royal Military Police has been delegated to General Officer Commanding 3rd United Kingdom Division. General Officer Commanding Regional Command has administrative control for the remaining elements of the Brigade.}}</ref>\n** Special Investigation Branch Regiment (SIB Regt) in Bulford\n** Special Operations Unit Royal Military Police in [[Bordon and Longmoor Military Camps|Longmoor]]{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n** [[Military Corrective Training Centre]] in Colchester\n\n==== 38th (Irish) Brigade ====\n* '''[[38 (Irish) Brigade|38th (Irish) Brigade]]''', in [[Thiepval Barracks|Lisburn]]\n\n==== 160th (Welsh) Brigade ====\n* '''[[160th (Welsh) Brigade]]''', in [[The Barracks, Brecon|Brecon]]\n\n=== Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command ===\nMajor-General [[Paul Nanson]] CBE is titled General Officer Commanding Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command, and Commandant Sandhurst. This means that his time is split between his Headquarters in Upavon and Academy HQ at Sandhurst. Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command was established on 1 April 2018.<ref name=ZacchiFOI /> Major-General [[Chris Bell (British Army officer)|Chris Bell]] will become GOC Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command in April 2020 and GOC Sandhurst will be separately held by Major-General Duncan Duncan Capps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf|title=Generals: February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nARITC oversees the Army Recruiting Group, which includes the National Recruitment Centre (NRC) and local Army Careers Centres, and is staffed by a mixture of [[Capita]] staff and Army personnel.<ref>Parliamentary Question 164313, Army Reserve Recruitment, asked by Mrs Madeleine Moon (Bridgend), 16 July 2018, Hansard Extracts https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2018-07-16.164311.h</ref>\n\n=== Army Personnel Centre ===\nThe Centre is located in [[Glasgow]]. The APC's Chief Executive is the [[Military Secretary (United Kingdom)|Military Secretary]], who also holds the post of [[Scottish Command|General Officer, Scotland]]. The APC deals with personnel issues and contact with outside agencies.\n\n=== Sandhurst Group ===\n{{main|Royal Military Academy Sandhurst}}\nCommandant Sandhurst is a Major-General, as of February 2020 dual-hatted as GOC ARITC.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf |title=Generals January 2020 |last=Mackie |first=Colin |date=5 January 2020 |via=gulabin.com |access-date=5 January 2020 |quote=Major-General Paul A.E. Nanson Commandant, Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst, September 2015-March 2020, and General Officer Commanding, Army Recruiting and Initial Training Command, April 2018-April 2020}}</ref> Major General [[Duncan Capps]] will be the next Commandant in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Generals-Current.pdf|title=Generals February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>  The day to day running of the Academy is devolved to a Brigadier, currently Brigadier James Carr-Smith who is titled Commander Sandhurst Group and responsible for:\n* Royal Military Academy Sandhurst\n* [[Army Officer Selection Board]], Westbury\n* [[University Officer Training Corps]]\n* Junior Staff Centre (Warminster)\n\n== Army units under other commands ==\n\n=== Strategic Command ===\nHeadquarters '''[[Strategic Command (United Kingdom)|Strategic Command]]''', [[Northwood Headquarters]], northwest London\n* [[42 Engineer Regiment (Geographic)]] at [[RAF Wyton]], [[Huntingdon]]\n* '''[[Director Special Forces]]''' in London\n** [[Special Air Service#22 SAS Regiment|22 Special Air Service Regiment]] at [[Stirling Lines]], Credenhill\n** [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] at Stirling Lines\n** [[18 (UKSF) Signal Regiment|18 Signal Regiment]] at Stirling Lines\n** [[Special Forces Support Group]] at [[MOD St Athan]]\n** [[Joint Special Forces Aviation Wing]] at [[RAF Odiham]]\n*** [[No. 658 Squadron AAC]] at [[Stirling Lines]] with [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin|Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin II]] and [[A\u00e9rospatiale Gazelle|Gazelle AH1]] helicopters\n* '''[[Permanent Joint Headquarters]]'''\n** Commander, [[British Forces South Atlantic Islands]] (BFSAI) ([[RAF Mount Pleasant]])\n*** Falkland Island Roulement Company from a 1st (United Kingdom) Division infantry regiment\n*** [[Falkland Islands Defence Force]] (Company sized)\n*** Air Defence Battery from 16th Regiment Royal Artillery\n*** Joint Communications Unit Royal Signals\n*** Engineer Detachment\n*** Royal Logistics Corps Detachment\n** '''[[British Forces Gibraltar]]''' in [[Gibraltar]]\n*** [[Royal Gibraltar Regiment]] \u2013 under the [[Queen's Division]]\n** Commander, '''[[British Forces Cyprus]]''' ([[British Sovereign Base Areas]], [[Cyprus]])\n*** 1st Battalion, [[Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment|The Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment (Queen's and Royal Hampshires)]], in [[Dhekelia Cantonment|Dhekelia]]\n*** 2nd Battalion, [[Mercian Regiment|The Mercian Regiment (Cheshire, Worcesters & Foresters, and Staffords)]], in [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]] (to move to [[Weeton Barracks]] and change roles with [[2 YORKS]])<ref name=ZacchiFOI />\n\n=== Fleet Commander, Royal Navy ===\n* '''[[3 Commando Brigade]] [[Royal Marines]]''' in Plymouth\n** Royal Marines units, including 40, 42, and 45 Commandos\n** [[24 Commando Regiment (United Kingdom)|24 Commando Regiment]] [[Royal Engineers]] in [[Royal Marines Base Chivenor|Chivenor]]\n** [[29th Commando Regiment Royal Artillery|29 Commando Regiment]] [[Royal Artillery]] in [[Plymouth]] with [[L118 light gun|L118]] 105mm towed howitzers\n** [[Commando Logistic Regiment]] in Chivenor\n*** [[383 Commando Petroleum Troop RLC|383 Commando Petroleum Troop]] [[Royal Logistic Corps]] in Plymouth\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of contemporary armies|British Army]]\n[[Category:Army 2020]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the British Army]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nThe [[British Army]] as a result of the [[Army 2020|Army 2020 Refine]] reforms are organised into two main commands, [[Commander Field Army|Field Army]] and [[Commander Home Command|Home Command]], each commanded by a [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|lieutenant general]].\n\n[[Permanent Joint Headquarters]] (PJHQ) plans and executes UK-led joint and multinational operations, including those involving British Army units, and operationally commands UK forces assigned to multinational operations led by other nation-states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/the-permanent-joint-headquarters|title=The Permanent Joint Headquarters|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> For example, during [[Operation Telic]], the Chief of Joint Operations at PJHQ directed Major General [[Robin Brims]], the UK Land Contingent Commander, through the UK National Contingent Commander, [[Air Marshal]] [[Brian Burridge]].<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20171123124640/http://www.iraqinquiry.org.uk/media/247900/the-report-of-the-iraq-inquiry_section-80.pdf The Report of the Iraqi Inquiry: The Invasion], pages 7 & 8, paragraphs 23, 25, 26.</ref>\n\nBritish Army forces may also be deployed to NATO operations, which then are delegated by [[North Atlantic Council]] or other NATO bodies to the [[Supreme Allied Commander Europe]] who delegates the operation to relevant headquarters. PJHQ may still be involved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmdfence/347/34717.htm#note463 |title=Fourteenth Report: Lessons of Kosovo III THE CONDUCT OF THE CAMPAIGN:Command, Coordination and Intelligence  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 October 2000 |website=publications.parliament.uk |publisher=Defence Select Committee |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|UK Army 2018.png|4400px|Structure of the British Army 2018-19|550px|right}}\n\n== Field Army ==\n{{see also|Commander Field Army}}\nThe units under Field Army are:<ref name=\"aff\">[http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf Regular Army basing matrix by formation and unit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814181412/http://www.aff.org.uk/linkedfiles/aff/latest_news_information/cregulararmybasingannouncementgridunclas.pdf |date=2016-08-14 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf Army 2020 Update] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610215557/http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report.pdf |date=June 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n* '''Reaction forces''' comprising [[16 Air Assault Brigade]] and 3rd (UK) Division of two armoured infantry brigades, the 12th and 20th Armoured Infantry Brigades, and two Strike brigades: 1st Strike Brigade and an as-yet-unnamed strike brigade, along with combat support units.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/9911295/Famed-Desert-Rats-to-lose-their-tanks-under-Army-cuts.html|title=Famed Desert Rats to lose their tanks under Army cuts|work=Telegraph|date=2013-03-05|accessdate=2013-03-09|last1=Kirkup|first1=James}}</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them as \"Armoured Infantry Brigades\"]</ref><ref name=\"Dec162\"/> 3rd UK Division is operationally affiliated with the [[Allied Rapid Reaction Corps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arrc.nato.int/about-us/formations |title=Assigned Formations |date= 31 January 2018 |website=arrc.nato.int |publisher=Allied Rapid Reaction Corps |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Adaptive forces''' comprising a 1st (UK) Division brigades, three of which (the 4th, 7th, and 51st) will be deployable.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/136406/regular_army_basing_plan.pdf Army Basing Plan: The basing plan table labels them in order]</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexA.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex A]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rfca-yorkshire.org.uk/files/TransformingtheBritishArmyAnnexC.pdf Transforming the British Army Annex C]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''6th (UK) Division''' comprising surveillance, intelligence, reconnaissance, communications, electronic warfare, psychological operations.\n* '''Joint Helicopter Command''' which commands most of the UK's battlefield lift and attack helicopters for the Royal Navy, British Army and Royal Air Force.\n\nField Army gained initial operating capability on 30 November 2015 and was formed as a result of the  2015 Army Command Review. The Commander Field Army commands all the formations of the British Army's forces for operational tasks, its collective training and tactical doctrine organisations and includes the vast majority of the Army\u2019s fighting equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |title=Flag raised to signal new HQ Field Army |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=26 August 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124164925/http://www.army.mod.uk/news/28058.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== 1st (United Kingdom) Division ===\n* '''[[1st (United Kingdom) Division]]''',<ref name=\"Army 2019\">{{cite web |title=Army restructures to confront evolving threats |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/army-restructures-to-confront-evolving-threats |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref> in [[York]] (Adaptable Force)\n\n==== 4th Infantry Brigade and Headquarters North East ====\n{{Location map+ | United Kingdom\n| width = 330\n| caption = <center> 1st (United Kingdom) Division brigade locations 2020</center>\n| relief = 1\n| places =\n{{Location map~ | United Kingdom\n    | label = <small>[[York|'''1 (UK) Div.''']